06:06.864 --> 06:07.914
Has anybody
ever dreamed

06:07.948 --> 06:11.150
About being Jimmy Olsen,
Superman's pal?

06:11.185 --> 06:12.719
Someone
of Superman's stature

06:12.753 --> 06:15.421
Considers you his best friend,
his pal?

06:15.456 --> 06:17.156
If Superman
were my friend,

06:17.191 --> 06:19.225
I would milk that for as much
as I could get out of it.

06:19.259 --> 06:20.643
What's the first thing
you'd do?

06:20.694 --> 06:22.361
I don't--
you know, I could have him

06:22.396 --> 06:23.863
Fly me to anywhere
I wanted to go.

06:23.897 --> 06:26.115
Oh, okay, "Hey, Superman, can
you be my personal jetliner?"

06:26.150 --> 06:27.767
Are you going to sit
on his back?

06:27.801 --> 06:28.835
What do you do for him?

06:28.869 --> 06:30.336
They confide in each other,
right?

06:30.370 --> 06:31.437
Yes.

06:31.471 --> 06:33.306
He could tell me
all his female problems.

06:33.340 --> 06:35.875
Why would you think
the world's most perfect man

06:35.893 --> 06:37.209
Has female problems?

06:37.227 --> 06:38.845
And he depends on Ming
for advice.

06:38.879 --> 06:40.313
[laughter]

06:40.347 --> 06:41.814
- Hi.
- Hey, how's it going?

06:41.849 --> 06:44.583
Got some issues of Spider-Man
here, it's 11 books.

06:44.601 --> 06:45.952
All right, so you're looking
to move all these today?

06:45.986 --> 06:48.988
Yeah, if I can.

06:54.795 --> 06:56.629
But what if
I just took out the one

06:56.647 --> 06:59.332
- I had a real strong interest in?
- All right.

06:59.366 --> 07:01.117
The 101,
the first Morbius.

07:01.168 --> 07:03.453
Let me just see
what it looks like.

07:03.504 --> 07:05.238
Well, right off the bat,
it's--

07:05.272 --> 07:07.807
It's oddly cut.
It looks like it's--

07:07.825 --> 07:11.611
Some flaking up there.

07:11.645 --> 07:13.880
Does have
some spine damage,

07:13.914 --> 07:15.982
But not a bad-looking book,
you know?

07:16.016 --> 07:19.719
1971, that's an oldie
right there.

07:19.753 --> 07:22.388
We had a guy come in
with some very key issues--

07:22.422 --> 07:24.857
Amazing Spider-Man 101.

07:24.892 --> 07:27.860
That would be the death
of Gwen Stacy?

07:27.895 --> 07:30.729
That would be the birth
of the Living Vampire.

07:30.747 --> 07:32.248
- Morbius.
- Yes.

07:32.282 --> 07:36.102
Oh, Lord, and why exactly
was he "The Living Vampire"?

07:36.136 --> 07:38.604
I believe
the story goes

07:38.639 --> 07:40.923
That the code was in effect,
and the code said,

07:40.958 --> 07:44.126
You cannot use vampires
in your stories--

07:44.178 --> 07:47.914
You can't use the undead
in your story.

07:47.948 --> 07:49.515
So Marvel found their way
around it by going,

07:49.550 --> 07:52.101
"Oh, he's not dead.
He's living."

07:52.135 --> 07:54.687
He's a scientific vampire
created by science.

07:54.721 --> 07:56.022
He has to drink blood,

07:56.056 --> 07:58.391
But he's not dead.
[laughter]

07:58.425 --> 08:01.427
Ingenious way around it, man.
Code's like, "foiled again."

08:01.461 --> 08:03.362
And he was a cool-looking
character too, man.

08:03.397 --> 08:04.730
He had that long hair.

08:04.764 --> 08:05.982
He looked
kind of like a partridge,

08:06.033 --> 08:07.149
But a bad-ass partridge.

08:07.201 --> 08:09.035
Like a partridge
in a pear tree

08:09.069 --> 08:11.070
Or like a partridge
from The Partridge family?

08:11.104 --> 08:14.340
- Like Keith Partridge.
- Yeah.

08:14.374 --> 08:17.743
121,
death of Gwen Stacy.

08:17.778 --> 08:19.612
This one looks all right.
Got a nice...

08:19.646 --> 08:21.881
- Yeah.
