at me and Mike,

11:56.256 --> 11:58.624
And just maybe get
your work done.

11:58.658 --> 12:01.426
- I am.
- How's it going, guys?

12:01.444 --> 12:02.811
- Fine, how are you?
- Good.

12:02.862 --> 12:05.614
You guys want to check out some
G.I. Joe stuff I brought in?

12:05.648 --> 12:06.932
- Yeah, sure.
- Yeah?

12:06.950 --> 12:08.800
- Bring it over here.
- Did you say, "G.I. Joes"?

12:08.818 --> 12:11.353
I did say "G.I. Joes."
why, are you a fan?

12:11.404 --> 12:12.938
I am.
Are they vintage?

12:12.972 --> 12:14.106
Yeah.
Well, from the '80s.

12:14.140 --> 12:15.707
- No way.
- They're not the 12-inch size.

12:15.741 --> 12:26.134
Whoa.

12:26.185 --> 12:27.836
You know how the NHL has,
like, the original six?

12:27.870 --> 12:29.538
These are like
the original 12.

12:29.589 --> 12:30.839
It's full of the figures
that would have been

12:30.873 --> 12:32.724
In it in '82, '83.
Yeah.

12:32.759 --> 12:33.892
File cards are there.

12:33.927 --> 12:35.794
These were written
by Larry Hama.

12:35.828 --> 12:37.262
- Oh, really?
- Yeah.

12:37.297 --> 12:38.397
Cool thing
about this is,

12:38.431 --> 12:40.299
Back in the Vietnam era,
he was in the military.

12:40.333 --> 12:41.800
He based a lot
of these file cards

12:41.834 --> 12:43.402
From, like, military guys

12:43.436 --> 12:45.437
That he knew
that were actually in 'nam.

12:45.471 --> 12:46.872
He also had
the little file cards

12:46.906 --> 12:49.157
That had little factoids
about them--

12:49.208 --> 12:51.743
Where they came from,
what their specialties were,

12:51.777 --> 12:53.345
What their favorite food was.

12:53.379 --> 12:54.680
- Favorite food?
- Yeah.

12:54.714 --> 12:56.381
- How does that play into it?
- It just--

12:56.416 --> 12:57.466
- Personalities.
- Oh, yeah?

12:57.517 --> 12:58.600
All of a sudden,
all these little figures

12:58.635 --> 13:00.752
Had, you know,
vast personalities.

13:00.787 --> 13:03.572
Ooh, he likes french fries.
So much more fun.

13:03.606 --> 13:05.023
Yeah.
Or, you know, that guy, he was

13:05.058 --> 13:07.092
From Cleveland, Ohio.
That's where I was born.

13:07.126 --> 13:08.577
We didn't know what
han solo's favorite food was

13:08.611 --> 13:10.395
When we were collecting
those figures.

13:10.430 --> 13:11.563
That's true,
and I felt empty for it.

13:11.597 --> 13:13.065
[laughter]

13:13.099 --> 13:14.633
G.I. Joe,
when they re-launched it in '82

13:14.667 --> 13:17.869
With these toys was
kind of based on S.H.I.E.L.D.

13:17.887 --> 13:20.138
And the bad guys, cobra,
were based on...

13:20.173 --> 13:21.173
- Hydra.
- Hydra.

13:21.207 --> 13:23.108
- What's up, man?
- Now you know.

13:23.142 --> 13:24.476
Dad?

13:24.510 --> 13:26.078
Hey, son.

13:26.112 --> 13:28.163
[laughter]

13:28.197 --> 13:30.198
Got some G.I. Joes
in the house.

13:30.249 --> 13:32.701
No wonder Ming is standing
at full attention.

13:32.752 --> 13:35.821
It's funny that--everyone's
definition of "bad-ass."

13:35.855 --> 13:38.657
He has his.
He's like, "this is bad-ass."

13:38.691 --> 13:40.859
A 2inch figure?
[laughter]

13:40.893 --> 13:43.045
- 3 3/4 inch.
- 3 3/4 inch.

13:43.096 --> 13:45.197
Size means everything,
Ming.

13:45.231 --> 13:47.232
[laughter]

13:47.266 --> 13:48.333
Did you have these
when you were a kid?

13:48.368 --> 13:50.335
This I wanted,
didn't get it though,

13:50.370 --> 13:51.837
'cause this was
a high-ticket item.

13:51.871 --> 13:53.472
This was either a birthday
or a christmas present.

13:53.506 --> 13:56.508
Yeah, it's pretty cool,
man.

14:02.048 --> 14:04.649
- Oh.
- Wow.

14:04.684 --> 14:05.650
Oh, that's pretty cool.

14:05.668 --> 14:07.119
- Oh.
- I'll show you.

14:07.153 --> 14:09.988
So it has wheels that pop out,
cockpit comes down.

14:10.023 --> 14:13.025
- Little pilot goes inside there.
- Oh, wow.

14:13.059 --> 14:14.242
You know, they don't make toys
like this anymore, man.

14:14.277 --> 14:15.494
Not at all.
Not this in-depth.

14:15.528 --> 14:16.745
This, I remember,

14:16.779 --> 14:19.331
When my brother and I found it
at the toy store,

14:19.365 --> 14:20.499
We actually hugged.

14:20.533 --> 14:22.250
There may have been some tears.
[laughter]

14:22.285 --> 14:25.804
I think my parents
felt sorry for us, that we--

14:25.838 --> 14:26.938
- That you guys were crying.
- Yeah.

14:26.973 --> 14:28.373
Yeah.
Tears of joy.

14:28.408 --> 14:30.575
And I think my parents probably
felt so bad that they--

14:30.609 --> 14:33.412
- They were just ashamed
to see their two sons

14:33.446 --> 14:34.579
Crying like blubbering
little girls over toys.

14:34.613 --> 14:35.964
18year-old dudes.

14:35.998 --> 14:37.049
They were just like,
"let's get them out of here."

14:37.083 --> 14:39.251
[laughter]

14:39.285 --> 14:40.852
These can go
for a lot of money now.

14:40.887 --> 14:41.953
Oh, yeah.

14:41.988 --> 14:43.121
It's like,
I remember the AT-AT

14:43.155 --> 14:45.590
From the original
Empire Strikes Back.

14:45.624 --> 14:47.592
I wanted it so badly,
man.

14:47.627 --> 14:49.161
One christmas,
I did get it.

14:49.195 --> 14:50.996
My mother
very seriously told me,

14:51.030 --> 14:52.798
She was like,
"This is from me and dad,

14:52.832 --> 14:54.365
"but this set us back
a lot,

14:54.383 --> 14:56.034
"so this is going
to be for christmas,

14:56.069 --> 14:58.570
Your birthday,
and next christmas,"

14:58.604 --> 14:59.571
And I didn't even care,
dude.

14:59.589 --> 15:01.339
I was just like,
"thank you so much.

15:01.374 --> 15:03.275
This is amazing."

15:03.309 --> 15:06.011
Cut to ten years later,

15:06.045 --> 15:07.179
We're having
a family chitchat

15:07.213 --> 15:08.630
About our favorite toys
and whatnot.

15:08.681 --> 15:09.748
Me, my brother,
and my sister,

15:09.782 --> 15:11.633
Around my parents,
and I was talking about,

15:11.684 --> 15:12.851
"Then there was
that christmas

15:12.885 --> 15:14.369
That mom and dad got me
the AT-AT."

15:14.403 --> 15:17.021
My brother goes, "Mom and dad
didn't get you the AT-AT.

15:17.039 --> 15:18.406
Aunt Rose
got you that AT-AT."

15:18.458 --> 15:20.542
[all groan]
- Really?

15:20.576 --> 15:22.511
I said, "Wait a second,
that came from mom and dad."

15:22.545 --> 15:23.995
And then mom and dad
were like,

15:24.013 --> 15:26.364
"We're going to go get some
coffee cake in the kitchen."

15:26.399 --> 15:27.966
And they took
cyanide capsules.

15:28.000 --> 15:29.501
[laughter]

15:29.535 --> 15:32.387
"he knows!"

15:32.438 --> 15:34.940
I'm not really interested
in the figures,

15:34.974 --> 15:36.975
But this I like.

15:37.009 --> 15:40.545
How much you looking for
for Night Raven?

15:40.580 --> 15:41.763
I could take $175
for the Night Raven.

15:41.798 --> 15:44.416
- $175?
- Yeah.

15:44.450 --> 15:45.817
Could you do $75?

15:45.852 --> 15:48.687
[exhales] Definitely can't go
that low at $75.

15:48.721 --> 15:49.754
I could do $150.

15:49.789 --> 15:54.276
Can you do $100?

15:54.310 --> 15:55.593
Yeah, I can do $100.

15:55.611 --> 15:57.362
It will look good
in the store.

15:57.396 --> 15:58.930
Yo, Joe!
Right?

15:58.965 --> 16:00.549
- Yep.
- All right.

16:00.583 --> 16:02.267
He's just like,
"Give me the money."

16:02.301 --> 16:05.803
All right.
$100.

16:05.822 --> 16:06.805
- Thank you, sir.
- Thank you.

16:06.839 --> 16:09.374
- Yo, Joe.
- Yo, Joe!

16:09.408 --> 16:12.027
- Calm down.
- Come on.

16:12.078 --> 16:13.645
You were going to give him
some other kind of "Yo, Joe"

16:13.663 --> 16:15.580
The way you were slobbering...

16:15.615 --> 16:18.016
- What the hell does that mean?
- All over everything.

16:18.050 --> 16:19.234
Whoa.
Check it out, man.

16:19.268 --> 16:20.986
- Hey.
- Star Wars fan?

16:21.020 --> 16:24.256
- Just a little bit, yeah.
- Holy crap.

16:28.508 --> 16:29.975
Hey, you were around

16:30.010 --> 16:31.844
During the first major comics
crossover, right?

16:31.878 --> 16:33.729
Let me take you back
to '76.

16:33.780 --> 16:36.115
America is celebrating
the bicentennial.

16:36.149 --> 16:37.399
Okay.

16:37.451 --> 16:38.517
And Marvel and DC

16:38.552 --> 16:41.253
Announce the first
intercompany crossover,

16:41.288 --> 16:42.922
And it was breathtaking.

16:42.956 --> 16:44.457
Spider-Man
versus Superman.

16:44.491 --> 16:45.958
What's
your favorite crossover?

16:45.992 --> 16:48.027
- Be all, end all?
- Yeah.

16:48.061 --> 16:50.896
Archie met the Punisher
in the '90s.

16:50.914 --> 16:51.981
- [laughing]
- Yeah.

16:52.032 --> 16:53.699
Did he take him on
as an apprentice?

16:53.733 --> 16:55.000
No,
he came to Riverdale.

16:55.034 --> 16:56.619
I guess some kids were selling
some crack or something.

16:56.653 --> 16:57.970
Like,
Punisher kicks the door in,

16:58.004 --> 17:02.041
Archie's in a crack house,
going, "Come on, daddy.

17:02.075 --> 17:04.643
Let me just take a hit
off this glass."

17:04.678 --> 17:07.279
- Whoa, check it out, man.
- Hey.

17:07.314 --> 17:08.614
Holy crap.

17:08.647 --> 17:09.915
Going to see
what I can do with this.

17:09.933 --> 17:11.282
Star Wars fan?

17:11.317 --> 17:14.019
Just a bit.
Just a little bit, yeah.

17:14.054 --> 17:16.005
So you're looking to move
some Battleships today, huh?

17:16.039 --> 17:19.058
Yeah.

17:30.203 --> 17:32.571
So you're looking to move
all three of these, huh?

17:32.589 --> 17:33.572
- Yeah.
- How come?

17:33.590 --> 17:36.108
Well, my girlfriend,

17:36.142 --> 17:38.477
She lives in England,
and I want to fly her over.

17:38.511 --> 17:40.479
It's been six months now
over the internet,

17:40.513 --> 17:42.047
And I want her
to meet my family.

17:42.082 --> 17:44.116
But you know it's love though?

17:44.150 --> 17:47.253
I couldn't possibly make
this work for six months.

17:47.287 --> 17:49.188
Over the internet
if she wasn't--

17:49.222 --> 17:50.689
I remember
when I first met my wife.

17:50.724 --> 17:52.558
I would have sold anything
like this gentleman

17:52.592 --> 17:54.360
If she lived
across the pond.

17:54.394 --> 17:57.213
You ever dome some kind
of large, romantic gesture.

17:57.264 --> 17:59.965
That's, like, completely
out of character for you?

18:00.000 --> 18:01.350
You were a part of it.

18:01.401 --> 18:03.135
You proposed to my wife
for me.

18:03.153 --> 18:05.271
Oh, my god, that's right.
I was involved.

18:05.305 --> 18:07.239
[laughing]

18:07.274 --> 18:08.874
Walter wanted
to propose to his lady,

18:08.909 --> 18:11.810
So his thing was,
he was holding up a big sign

18:11.845 --> 18:14.113
That said,
"Marry me, Debbie."

18:14.147 --> 18:16.348
I was to simply go
into the school,

18:16.382 --> 18:18.267
Knock on her door,
and to instruct her

18:18.318 --> 18:19.385
To look out the window.

18:19.419 --> 18:22.788
So I knock on the door.
I said, "Hi, Deb.

18:22.822 --> 18:25.524
Walter would like you
to look out the window."

18:25.559 --> 18:27.326
And her first response,

18:27.360 --> 18:30.362
She goes, "Why?"
[laughter]

18:30.397 --> 18:32.147
He comes sailing off the roof
with a noose around his neck.

18:32.198 --> 18:34.733
"This is for you, Damien."
[laughter]

18:34.768 --> 18:36.802
What are you looking to get
for these three?

18:36.836 --> 18:38.954
I'm looking at $750.

18:39.005 --> 18:40.806
Whoa, she's not taking
a Starship here, is she?

18:40.840 --> 18:43.609
[laughter]

18:43.643 --> 18:44.677
What's the Millennium Falcon

18:44.711 --> 18:46.595
And an Imperial Shuttle

18:46.646 --> 18:48.547
And a Starship
go for nowadays?

18:48.582 --> 18:50.983
I remember picking this one up
for, like, $55, $60.

18:51.001 --> 18:52.351
Okay.

18:52.385 --> 18:55.254
I mean, this one's
maybe worth around $95 now.

18:55.288 --> 18:58.123
- Imperial Shuttle.
- Maybe about $200.

18:58.158 --> 19:00.459
- So that goes for $200.
- Yeah, the Starship.

19:00.493 --> 19:04.096
Think this one goes probably
around the $200 range.

19:04.130 --> 19:06.982
Well, I'm glad you're here.
Never heard that before, right?

19:07.017 --> 19:08.017
Oh, very rarely.

19:08.068 --> 19:11.604
Especially at home. [laughter]

19:11.638 --> 19:17.476
I could offer you,
for these three ships...

19:17.510 --> 19:18.627
$250.

19:18.662 --> 19:20.579
At $250,
I'd have to ship her U.P.S.

19:20.597 --> 19:22.047
You know,
I got to find something

19:22.082 --> 19:24.583
- A little more than that.
- $350.

19:24.617 --> 19:26.085
Is there any way
we can do more than $350?

19:26.119 --> 19:30.422
Any way, with all the love
in your heart?

19:30.457 --> 19:32.975
$450.

19:33.009 --> 19:34.827
$600?

19:34.861 --> 19:36.161
$500?

19:36.196 --> 19:38.631
$550.

19:38.665 --> 19:40.833
[groans] No.

19:40.867 --> 19:42.134
Not a chance, brother.
Take $500.

19:42.168 --> 19:43.686
So then $500 it is!
Sounds great.

19:43.737 --> 19:45.604
- $500 sounds great.
- All right.

19:45.639 --> 19:47.239
- All right.
- $500.

19:47.273 --> 19:49.608
All right, man, I really hope
you don't screw this up, man.

19:49.643 --> 19:51.210
Get her over here.
Get a ring on her finger.

19:51.244 --> 19:54.213
Come back
and tell me 20 years from now--

19:54.247 --> 19:56.548
- I spent the money
on bath salts.

19:56.583 --> 19:57.783
[laughter]

19:57.817 --> 19:59.001
- All right.
- Pressure's on.

19:59.035 --> 20:00.152
Can't tell you
what this means to me.

20:00.170 --> 20:01.286
- Thank you.
- Thanks, Mike.

20:01.304 --> 20:02.721
- It will go to a good home.
- Thank you.

20:02.756 --> 20:03.856
Good luck.

20:03.890 --> 20:06.091
That's
some serious long distance.

20:06.109 --> 20:07.593
It worked for me though.

20:07.627 --> 20:09.228
Me and my wife had
a long-distance relationship

20:09.262 --> 20:10.229
For, like, three years.

20:10.263 --> 20:12.381
How tough was that?

20:12.415 --> 20:15.334
It wasn't easy,
and I was going nuts, man.

20:15.368 --> 20:17.736
I never knew
you were this, like--

20:17.771 --> 20:19.505
- Yeah.

20:19.539 --> 20:21.940
[laughter]

20:21.975 --> 20:23.108
I'm going to get you something
to take your mind off it.

20:23.126 --> 20:24.343
Okay.

20:24.377 --> 20:27.079
I guess, price these,
put 'em up somewhere,

20:27.113 --> 20:29.531
And see if we can make back
the money at least.

20:29.582 --> 20:31.300
- Okay, all right.
- Thanks.

20:31.351 --> 20:35.421
This is the first one going up.

20:35.455 --> 20:38.424
- He's a freak, ain't he?
- Adds "horn dog" to his resume.

20:38.458 --> 20:40.592
[laughter]

20:40.627 --> 20:42.416
Sex, comic books, hockey--

20:42.417 --> 20:44.403
All the good things
come to an end, kids.

20:44.404 --> 20:45.704
Just like this show.

20:45.705 --> 20:48.105
Thanks for hanging out
with me and the comic book men.

20:48.106 --> 20:50.034
Until next week.
I'm your host, Kevin Smith.

20:50.035 --> 20:52.054
- Bryan Johnson.
- Walt Flanagan.

20:52.055 --> 20:53.555
- Mike Zapcic.
- Ming Chen.

20:53.556 --> 20:54.856
Don't make us angry.

20:54.857 --> 20:56.857
You wouldn't like us
when we're angry.
